How good is New Zealand at Driving and Parking

How good is New Zealand at driving and parking?

This reports aim is to explain data collected on New Zealands driving by analyzing the number of traffic violations that occur in a day, the vehicle which committed the most of these violations, and how well the parking was overall.



Graph of distribution of most Violations:



The above bar chart shows us the frequency of rankings given throughout the period of data collection. It filters this by the vehicle that was observed breaking the most violations on the day. From this chart we would expect that the mean parking rating to be around 5. We also notice that it appears that more rankings of lower than 5 were given than higher than 5 so we’d expect this number to lean towards 4 rather than 6.

This is confirmed by taking the mean of our data (rounded to 1dp) which is: 5.2. This is notably different from our prior data where it leaned more to 6 than 4, and is getting to the middle ground of the data which we’d expect if we had a normal distribution.

Graph of distribution of parking scale:

Distribution of parking scale



The above scatter plot shows us the parking ranking on a scale of 1 to 10, based on the hour of the day, and is filtered by the vehicle that committed the most violations on that day. We notice that it looks pretty linear, it appears to follow a trend that the later the day gets the higher the parking ranking, the data appears to have its majority centered around 12-16 hours (12pm to 4pm) for the most likely time to get a average value of 5. It is also interesting as we can see some patterns some vertical lines, which is quite interesting, particularly around parking rating of 3,5,7,8 which show us the most likely picked ratings, and the lines are to be expected given what we are measuring and that the value has to be a positive whole number between 0-10. (0 is even and odd by definition (2k),(2k+1))

Graph of Distribution of most_violations being either “unsure” or “no”:

Distribution of most_violations being unsure or no



The last bar chart shows us the distribution of answers that were given when asked about what vehicle commited the most violations, it specifically looks for if the respondent was unsure or if there were no violations being observed. From this bar chart we can see that clearly there tends to be violations being committed on the majority of travels. Which does not side with New Zealand being good at driving as we are investigating. Only 6 out of 40 observations were either unsure or had no violations, 4 being no violations, 2 being unsure.

Conculsion:

From the data we have collected we can infer that New Zealands parking is slightly higher than what we’d expect (5) on a scale of 1-10 ie, being average. However the amount of violations committed is very high, with very few trips observing no violations only one tenth of the data being such. Thus overall we can infer that New Zealand is not very good at driving and is about average on parking.
